WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.400
Hi, I'm Lucy D'Agostino McGowan, and I'm excited to talk to you about designing randomized

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:17.920
studies using Shiny. You can find me on Twitter at LucyStats, and you can find these slides

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:24.320
at lucymcgowan.com slash talk. So the work I'm going to be talking about today was done

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:29.000
in collaboration with students in my data science lab at Wake Forest University. In

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.119
particular, Jonathan Trattner and Nuri Park, and you can find some of our other projects

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:41.480
at dmds.lucymcgowan.com. Okay, so I'm going to show you four ways we can leverage the

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:48.400
power of Shiny to help streamline our randomized study design via informed consent, randomization,

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:55.599
collecting demographics, and incorporating learnr modules. So informed consent. Informed

00:00:55.599 --> 00:01:00.959
consent is a common process when involving human subjects in a trial. Often you hand

00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:06.040
people a piece of paper, and they either say that they agree to be in a study or they don't.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.400
And so instead of that, we can actually have the entire process completed online from the

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:14.000
comfort of your participants' browsers. And so we're basically going to leverage Shiny

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.680
such that if the user consents, they're sent to the study. And if they don't, then they're

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:26.680
sent back to the homepage. And so in Shiny, we often work with two components, the user

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:32.839
interface, what the user sees, and the server, what runs behind the scenes in R. And so here's

00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:38.760
some code for the user interface to be able to incorporate the consent here. And so first,

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:45.120
you can incorporate the consent text via an HTML document, for example. And then you can

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:49.419
use an action button function to create a nice action button that will either send the

00:01:49.419 --> 00:01:56.419
participant to the study if they agree, or back to the homepage if not. So on the server

00:01:56.419 --> 00:02:02.419
side, we need to check whether the user clicked yes or no, and then send them somewhere accordingly.

00:02:02.419 --> 00:02:06.220
And so this function will check if the user clicked yes, and if they did, it's going to

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:11.259
open a new window and send them to the link. I'm doing this using render UI, so I need

00:02:11.259 --> 00:02:16.059
to make sure to update the user interface with that UI output so that this actually

00:02:16.139 --> 00:02:22.699
works. And so that's what this is doing here, this UI output. And then OpenStudy was the ID

00:02:22.699 --> 00:02:27.179
that I gave that output in the server. So now that will actually send them to the link.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:33.100
So one of the coolest things about using Shiny for this is that it gives you the power of R

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:39.020
from the web browser. So we can actually randomize participants at the time of consent.

00:02:39.020 --> 00:02:45.259
So it basically really streamlines that process. So we just need to update the server a little

00:02:45.259 --> 00:02:50.300
bit to do that. And so essentially what I've done here is I've added a coin flip to determine

00:02:50.300 --> 00:02:56.300
which group the participant should be in. And then they're sent to a different link accordingly.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:03.660
So we're developing a package in R that does this and a few other neat features like generates user

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:09.740
IDs, saves a randomization list, allows for unique links for users, etc. It's very much

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:19.020
under development, but you can find it on GitHub at jdtrat.com. Okay, so now that we've randomized

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:25.259
folks, let's collect some demographics. So we have another package called Shiny Surveys

00:03:25.259 --> 00:03:28.699
that can help with this. And this one actually is almost ready for prime time, so I encourage

00:03:28.699 --> 00:03:38.139
you to try it. You can install it from GitHub at jdtrat.com. And so basically what this package

00:03:38.139 --> 00:03:44.779
allows you to do is it lets you pass a data frame with questions, options, input types, dependencies,

00:03:44.779 --> 00:03:50.059
etc. And a nice shiny questionnaire is going to be generated for you that can then be incorporated

00:03:50.059 --> 00:03:57.979
in your application. And so in R, it's as easy as just loading the package and then using the

00:03:57.979 --> 00:04:03.419
survey output function in the user interface, passing the data frame with your questions in it.

00:04:03.419 --> 00:04:11.339
And so here my data frame is called D. And then using render survey in the server function,

00:04:11.339 --> 00:04:16.299
and this will, you also will pass it that same data frame, and this will automatically generate

00:04:16.299 --> 00:04:22.540
a nice survey. It'll look something like this, where it has the questions as well as the different

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:27.899
places to input. You can have required questions with those little stars. You can also have

00:04:27.899 --> 00:04:32.940
dependencies. For example, if you answer a certain way, then new questions can pop up accordingly.

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:40.859
So finally, all of this can be incorporated in commonly used shiny tools like LearnR modules.

00:04:40.859 --> 00:04:45.899
So for example, LearnR modules can record all of the user's input data, which can be great

00:04:45.899 --> 00:04:51.100
for a study. And you can stick the user IDs generated from the task designer package in here,

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:55.019
and then you can save this data with a unique ID that can be linked to the demographic data

00:04:55.019 --> 00:05:01.579
for later analysis. So that's all. You can find me at LucyStats on Twitter. Thank you so much.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:04.380
Bye.

